# Global Agent Instructions

Cross-project guidelines and gotchas for AI coding agents.

## Shell Quoting Pitfalls

### Literal `\n` in Single-Quoted Strings

When passing descriptions or multi-line content to CLI tools, **single-quoted strings treat `\n` as literal backslash-n, not a newline.**

```bash
# BAD — \n stays literal
linear-cli i create "Title" -t ENG -d 'Line 1\nLine 2\n\nLine 3'

# GOOD — use JSON with proper \n escaping
linear-cli i create "Title" -t ENG --data '{"description":"Line 1\nLine 2\n\nLine 3"}'

# Also GOOD — use double quotes with actual newlines
linear-cli i create "Title" -t ENG -d "Line 1
Line 2

Line 3"
```

**Applies to:** `linear-cli`, `gh`, and any tool accepting descriptions via `-d` or `--data` flags.

### Heredoc Gotcha

When using `--data` with a heredoc, the JSON parser interprets `\n` correctly (it's valid JSON escape syntax). But `-d` with a heredoc passes raw text — use `--data` for proper JSON parsing.

## Linear CLI Patterns

### Creating Child Issues

```bash
linear-cli i create "Sub-issue Title" -t TEAM --data '{"parentId":"PARENT-ISSUE"}'
```

The `parentId` field links the new issue as a child. Works for any parent issue in the same team.

### Draft / Placeholder Issues

When creating placeholder or proposed issues (not final requirements), mark them clearly:

```bash
linear-cli i create "Title" -t TEAM --data '{
  "parentId":"PARENT-ISSUE",
  "description":"**Status:** Draft / Placeholder\n**Owner:** TBD\n\nDescription text.\n\nThis is a proposed sub-issue. It is a draft idea, not an official requirement."
}'
```

### JSON vs Flags

Prefer `--data` with JSON over individual flags when setting multiple fields. It avoids shell quoting issues and is more maintainable.

## General Patterns

- Always use `--data` with JSON (not `-d` with plain strings) for multi-line descriptions.
- Prefer `--dry-run` to preview before creating issues.
- Use `--id-only` when scripting to get clean output for chaining.
- For updates, use `--data` JSON as well — it supports the same field names as create.
